vectorData.altText: 33. The major vessels posterior to the knee are the _____________ artery and vein.
That's right!  The popliteal artery and vein are the major vessels posterior to the knee and are located within the popliteal fossa.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The popliteal fossa provides the major route by which structures pass between the thigh and the leg. It is a diamond-shaped regions posterior to the knee, analogous to the cubital fossa in the upper limb.

Immediately inferolateral and inferomedial to your popliteal fossa, palpate the two heads of the gastrocnemius muscles, which are known colloquially as the “calf muscles”. 
Recall, from your study of the thigh, that the femoral artery and vein pass from the anterior compartment of the thigh, through the adductor hiatus, and into the popliteal fossa, where they are called the popliteal artery and vein. Recall, further, that the tibial and common fibular divisions of the sciatic nerve pass from the posterior compartment of the thigh through the popliteal fossa to gain access to the leg. The popliteal fossa further contains lymphatic vessels and lymph nodes.
FEEL the cord-like tendon of your biceps femoris superolateral to your knee.

Similarly, feel the cord-like tendon of your semitendinosus superomedial to your knee.
These muscles form the superolateral and superomedial borders of the popliteal fossa, respectively.
